## Context

This section is beat 5 of the landing page — it follows the "vs rules
packs" section that names the mechanical differences between AIDE and
flat rules files. That section makes the argument in words; this section
makes it visually. The cascading intent tree is the single concept that
no rules pack can replicate: `.aide` specs live at multiple directory
levels, each child inheriting the parent's intent and narrowing it to
the slice of the problem it owns. Helpers have no specs. The tree shape
itself encodes the architecture. A visitor who sees this diagram should
understand the cascade without having read any methodology docs — the
visual does the teaching.

The diagram renders as a static typographic artifact in the same
monospace register as the install code block in beat 1. It is not an
interactive widget, not an animation, not a product demo. It reads as
engineering documentation: something a visitor could screenshot and paste
into a Slack thread and it would still make sense as a standalone image.

## Strategy

**Use a content-pipeline application as the example domain.** The parent
spec requires operational domains only — no legal, medical, tax, or
compliance. A content pipeline (ingest, transform, publish) is
immediately legible to the landing's two audiences (technical builders
and non-technical users describing what they want), uses everyday
vocabulary, and is a domain where iteration is cheap and stakes are
operational (root spec `outcomes.undesired` item 1; parent spec Strategy
"domain examples are operational, not regulated"). A content pipeline
also naturally decomposes into submodules with distinct responsibilities,
which makes the tree shape feel earned rather than contrived.

**Show four levels of the intent tree: project root, src, feature,
submodule.** The canonical spec defines the cascading intent tree as
running from `.aide/intent.aide` at the top down to the deepest module
spec (aide-spec.md, "Example: full project intent tree"). Four levels
are the minimum needed to demonstrate that intent narrows at each step
— fewer looks flat, more overwhelms the ten-second scan budget
(frontmatter `outcomes.undesired` item 4). The tree should show
approximately 15–20 lines total: enough to feel realistic, not so many
that the visitor's eye loses the pattern.

**Show two to three siblings at the feature level, one expanded to
submodule depth.** Expanding every branch would double the line count
without adding conceptual value. Expanding one branch to submodule depth
proves the cascade goes deeper; showing collapsed siblings proves the
pattern repeats horizontally. This mirrors the canonical example tree
structure in aide-spec.md lines 51–79, which shows one feature expanded
with submodules while keeping the overall tree scannable.

**Include at least one helper folder without a `.aide` spec.** The
placement rule — orchestrators have specs, helpers don't (aide-spec.md,
"Where `.aide` Files Live") — is a key differentiator from flat rules
files that apply globally. Showing a helper with no spec makes the
selective placement visible and teaches that AIDE specs are intentional,
not boilerplate. The helper's absence of a spec is as important as the
orchestrator's presence of one.

**Visually distinguish `.aide` files from code files using inline
annotations.** Each `.aide` file in the tree gets a short right-aligned
annotation (preceded by a left-arrow marker) that names what that spec
level does — e.g., "project-wide intent," "narrows to content pipeline,"
"narrows to ingestion." This is the mechanism that makes the cascading
relationship visible without requiring the visitor to read actual spec
content. Without annotations, the diagram is just a file tree that
happens to contain `.aide` files — indistinguishable from a generic
project listing (frontmatter `outcomes.undesired` item 2). The
annotation style matches the `aide_discover` tool output format, which
uses the same right-aligned description pattern.

**Do not annotate code files or helper folders.** Annotations are
reserved for `.aide` spec files. Code files (`index.ts`) and helper
folders appear in the tree for realism but carry no description. This
creates a visual contrast: the spec files are the annotated focal
points, the code files are the quiet supporting structure. The visitor's
eye is drawn to the annotations, which are the cascade.

**Render as a monospace code block, not a styled component tree.** The
diagram should use the same typographic treatment as the install config
block in beat 1 — monospace font, box-drawing characters for tree
branches, muted code-file entries, highlighted `.aide` entries. This
reads as an engineering artifact consistent with the rest of the page
(parent spec Strategy: "copy is hedge-free, short, declarative"). The
Evil Martians 100-site study found that code/config blocks as visual
elements are the dominant pattern for dev-tool landings that lack a UI
screenshot (skeptical-engineer-conversion research, Source 2). The
intent-tree diagram is another instance of that same pattern.

**Connect to beat 4 through visual proof, not redundant copy.** Beat 4
("vs rules packs") makes the persistence-gap argument in text: rules
packs are flat, AIDE cascades. Beat 5 is the visual receipt. The
diagram should not re-argue the comparison — no "unlike CLAUDE.md..."
copy. The tree structure IS the argument. A visitor who just read "rules
packs are flat unstructured lumps" and then sees a four-level cascading
tree with narrowing annotations gets the point without being told twice.
Problem-first storytelling over feature lists (Evil Martians 100-site
study, feature hierarchy ranking in skeptical-engineer-conversion
research, Source 2).

**Keep the section to one diagram with a single heading line above it.**
No explanatory paragraph between the heading and the tree. The heading
names what the visitor is looking at ("Intent cascades through the
project tree" or similar); the diagram does the rest. Additional prose
would push the diagram below the fold on shorter viewports and violate
the ten-second scan constraint. The diagram is self-explanatory by
design — if it needs a paragraph of explanation, the annotations are
not doing their job.

## Good examples

A heading reads "Intent cascades through the project tree." Directly
below it, a monospace code block:

```
content-pipeline/
├── .aide/
│   └── intent.aide           ← project-wide intent
├── src/
│   ├── .aide                 ← narrows to content domain
│   └── service/
│       ├── ingest/
│       │   ├── .aide         ← narrows to ingestion
│       │   ├── index.ts
│       │   ├── parseFeed/
│       │   │   ├── .aide     ← narrows to feed parsing
│       │   │   └── index.ts
│       │   └── normalize/
│       │       └── index.ts  (helper — no spec)
│       ├── transform/
│       │   ├── .aide         ← narrows to transformation
│       │   └── index.ts
│       └── publish/
│           ├── .aide         ← narrows to publishing
│           └── index.ts
```

The visitor's eye tracks the left-arrow annotations down the tree. Each
annotation uses the word "narrows," reinforcing the cascade concept
without requiring methodology vocabulary. The helper `normalize/` has
no `.aide` and no annotation — its absence is visible. The tree is
18 lines, scannable in under ten seconds. A visitor who just read the
"vs rules packs" section sees immediately that this is not a flat file
— it is a hierarchy where each level specializes the one above it. The
diagram could be screenshotted and pasted into a Slack thread as a
self-contained explanation of what AIDE does differently.

## Bad examples

A tree that shows only two levels — project root and one feature — with
no submodule expansion. This fails to demonstrate cascading: two levels
could be a flat config at the root plus one module override, which is
exactly what `.cursorrules` plus a local override looks like. The
cascade requires at least three spec levels (root, feature, submodule)
to be visually distinct from a flat-plus-override pattern.

A tree using regulated-domain module names:

```
legal-doc-analyzer/
├── .aide/
│   └── intent.aide
├── src/
│   └── service/
│       ├── contractReview/
│       │   ├── .aide
│       │   └── index.ts
│       └── complianceCheck/
│           ├── .aide
│           └── index.ts
```

This violates the parent spec's operational-not-regulated constraint.
A visitor seeing "contractReview" and "complianceCheck" will question
whether they should trust an AI methodology for legal work — and
they should not, because AIDE is not positioned for domains where
mistakes are irreversible.

A tree where every folder has a `.aide` file, including helpers:

```
├── parseFeed/
│   ├── .aide         ← validates feed format
│   └── index.ts
├── normalize/
│   ├── .aide         ← normalizes content shape
│   └── index.ts
```

This misrepresents the methodology. The placement rule is that helpers
do not have specs — their folder name and code are self-explanatory
(aide-spec.md). Showing specs on helpers makes AIDE look like
boilerplate overhead rather than selective, intentional documentation.

An interactive tree with expand/collapse controls, hover tooltips
showing spec content, and a smooth animation when branches open. This
reads as a product demo widget, not engineering documentation. The
parent spec requires a static typographic artifact — something that
works as a screenshot. Interactivity adds implementation complexity
without adding comprehension; the tree's shape is the argument, and
shape is visible at rest.

A tree with no annotations — just folder names and `.aide` files listed
alongside `index.ts` files with no visual distinction:

```
├── ingest/
│   ├── .aide
│   ├── index.ts
│   ├── parseFeed/
│   │   ├── .aide
│   │   └── index.ts
```

Without annotations, the `.aide` files blend into the file listing.
The cascading relationship is invisible — removing the `.aide` files
would leave an ordinary project tree. The annotations are what make
the inheritance and narrowing relationship the focal point.

A diagram preceded by two paragraphs of explanation: "The AIDE
methodology uses cascading intent specs that live next to your code.
Each spec inherits from its parent and narrows the intent to the
specific module it governs. Here is what that looks like in
practice..." This burns ten seconds of reading time before the
visitor even reaches the diagram, violating the scan-budget constraint.
If the diagram needs that much preamble, the annotations are failing.

## References

- `research/aidemd-dev/aide-positioning-landscape.md` -- "vs rules packs" differentiators: per-module cascading, falsifiable outcomes, QA pipeline; AIDE's one-line differentiator is "intent as the contract, not the prompt."
- `research/aidemd-dev/skeptical-engineer-conversion.md` -- Evil Martians 100-site study finding that code/config blocks serve as the dominant visual element for dev-tool landings; problem-first storytelling ranked strongest for early-stage products; above-the-fold clutter hurts technical credibility.
- `.aide/docs/aide-spec.md` -- Canonical definition of the cascading intent tree, the example project tree (lines 51-79), the inheritance rule, the placement rule (orchestrators have specs, helpers don't), and the "copy-paste sibling" test for spec specificity.
- `.aide/docs/progressive-disclosure.md` -- The three-tier model (folder structure, JSDoc, inline comments) that the diagram implicitly teaches by showing the tree as architecture.
- `src/components/LandingPage/.aide` (parent spec) -- Beat ordering (intent tree is beat 5 after vs-rules-packs), domain-example constraint (operational not regulated), static-typographic-artifact requirement, sixty-second reading budget, no interactivity rule.
- `.aide/intent.aide` (root spec) -- Project-wide constraint against regulated-domain positioning; v1 is Claude Code only; no marketing hedges.
